The spread of Islam in Sylhet is closely tied to the influence of Sufism, a mystical branch of Islam that emphasizes personal spiritual experiences and the guidance of spiritual leaders. Gazi Pir is often regarded as a Sufi saint, and his teachings are seen as a reflection of the Sufi tradition. The role of Sufism in the Islamization of Sylhet is a subject of ongoing research and debate, with scholars exploring the ways in which Sufi teachings and practices shaped the religious and cultural landscape of the region.

